This file contains instructions to test a custom chaincode on a local netowrk during development. This is useful as testing 
chaincode on the netowrk is time consuming.

Open three terminals and enter the hypreledger fabric-samples/chaincode-docker-devmode folder.


terminal 1
docker rm -f $(docker ps -aq)
docker-compose -f docker-compose-simple.yaml up

terminal 2
docker exec -it chaincode bash
cd chaincode_example02/node/
npm install fabric-shim
CORE_CHAINCODE_ID_NAME="chaincode_example02:v0" npm start -- --peer.address peer:7052

terminal 3 
docker exec -it cli bash
cd chaincode_example02/node/
peer chaincode install -l node -n chaincode_example02 -v v0 -p /opt/gopath/src/chaincodedev/chaincode/chaincode_example02/node/
peer chaincode instantiate -l node -n chaincode_example02 -v v0 -C myc -c '{"args":["init"]}'
peer chaincode query -C myc -n chaincode_example02 -c '{"Args":["query", "a"]}'
peer chaincode query -C myc -n chaincode_example02 -c '{"Args":["query", "b"]}'
peer chaincode invoke -n chaincode_example02 -C myc -c '{"Args":["invoke", "a", "b", "10"]}'

Note: Pass the appropriate values to the arguments as per your chaincode logic. Arguments in this example are specific to chaincode_example02
in the chaincode folder.
